  "prompt": "Why do jain sadhus do not wear clothes?",
  "response": "Jain sadhus (monks) often do not wear clothes as a part of their spiritual practice and commitment to their beliefs. Here are several key reasons for this practice:\n\n1. **Renunciation of Materialism**: Jainism emphasizes renunciation of material possessions and attachments. By not wearing clothes, sadhus demonstrate their rejection of material comforts and societal norms.\n\n2. **Non-violence (Ahimsa)**: Jains practice strict non-violence, which extends to their treatment of all living beings. Some monks believe that clothing, especially if made from animal products, contributes to harm. Going unclothed can be seen as a way to avoid causing harm to any living being.\n\n3. **Spiritual Purity**: For many Jain monks, shedding clothes symbolizes a higher state of purity and detachment from worldly concerns. It represents their focus on spiritual goals rather than physical appearances.\n\n4. **Tradition**: This practice is rooted in the traditions and teachings of Jainism, where specific sects have historically practiced nudity as a form of asceticism. The mode of dress (or lack thereof) has become an identity marker within the community.\n\n5. **Simplicity and Humility**: By not wearing clothes, sadhus express humility and simplicity, shunning ego and pride that may come with attire, status, or wealth.\n\nIt is important to note that not all Jains or Jain monks adopt this practice. Different sects and individuals may have varying interpretations of their beliefs and different practices regarding clothing.",
